==English==

===Etymology===
This expression was made popular by Judge Judy on her extremely high-rated television program. It seems to be a reference to the assassination of John F. Kennedy. The assassination seemed to be an open-and-shut case but many people raised the possibility that Kennedy was murdered by the CIA, the mafia, or was the victim of various other conspiracy theories. Therefore, anyone who bothers to ask "who shot John" is speaking foolishness as (it would seem) Kennedy's assassin was apprehended.

===Expression===
'''[[who]] [[shot]] [[John]]'''
# Rambling, distracting nonsensical talk.

====Usage notes====
Though it is an expression, it is always used as a noun, e.g. "Don't tell me the dog ate your homework, that's a lot of 'who shot John'!"

===Variant spellings===
*who-shot-John